children.value: Those goods belong to us all in the first place, so he is no thief. He simply needs to learn to reassess the extent of his needs. Persuasion goes a longer way than punishment, Dr. Hugo always insists on that!

children.name: Text
children.value: So long, coerced compliance of justice! A new anarchist approach is in town and it promises to resolve conflicts by actually listening to the people affected and working towards an agreeable solution!

children.name: Text
children.value: A merchant who'll pay a price to match the effort needed to produce a good, rather than the deflated value given it by the so-called "free" market? I'd never fall for such a blatant attempt to infiltrate us. Follow her ship, bring me proof of her true intentions.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Mercier highly doubts that someone as complicit to capitalism as a merchant would willingly pay the prices the labour theory of value dictates. He's convinced she's up to no good and has asked you to follow the merchant and inform him about her true colours.

children.name: Text
children.value: Utopian, naÃ¯ve, childish, preposterous... Oh, how those stuck-ups at the Medical School enjoyed mocking my ideals. But I have always been the better man. Yes, I will open up my doors to them, let them contemplate what they once laughed at. Bring them these formal invitations.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Mercier has not forgotten how his colleagues at the Medical School laughed at his anarchist ideas. But now that his dreams have become a reality, he has decided to extend a friendly invitation to them. Sounds like he can't wait to see the look on their faces...

children.name: Text
children.value: Sir Archibald Blake, that phony old man... I bet the peacocks on his back garden are better fed than most of his Queen's subjects. I despise those flamboyant creatures and everything they stand for... Yes, of course...! If you want to prove something, kidnap one of his precious peacocks!

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh! So this... this is the peacock, huh? Er-, yes... Yes! What you should do now...? Oh, I know, put it on your newspaper!

children.name: Text
children.value: In a fit of genius, Hugo has suggested you to steal one of Sir Archibald's peacocks. There seems to be a deeper meaning to the whole shenanigan that is not yet entirely clear to you...

children.name: Text
children.value: In an unexpected turn of events, our governor has decided to follow Dr. Hugo Mercier's hunch and steal one of Sir Archibald Blake's feathered pets. To what end, no one is yet entirely sure, but our editorial department has been informed that it is absolutely crucial!

children.name: Text
children.value: Von Malching, loathsome baron only of the vilest form of liberalism, must be overthrown! He's drilled fear deep into his workers' brains, they need a push â€”nay, inspiration!â€” to rise against their oppressor!

children.name: Text
children.value: Mercier thinks it's time for Von Malching's workers to realise that they have the power to put him in his place. He has tasked you with bringing some of his most brilliant instigators sneakily into his shores, so they can spark a revolution.

children.name: Text
children.value: What!? A riot!? No, no, no!! Stay where you are! I will not have this! Make them shut up, you incompetent milksops!!

children.name: Text
children.value: Slavery is murder. Property is theft. Merchants prance the waters carrying the stolen fruits of the workers' labour and claim to have the right to cut the hands of those who take back what's rightfully theirs. An enlightened soul would cut *their* hands...

children.name: Text
children.value: The very concept of "property" is in itself an abuse, an usurpation. Simply put: theft. Hugo claims merchants should be the ones paying the price for their crimes.

children.name: Text
children.value: A good friend of mine wrote that "the idea of God is the most decisive negation of human liberty, and necessarily ends in the enslavement of mankind." That church you have is indoctrinating your people into conformism. It is despicable. Many would celebrate you breaking those chains...

children.name: Text
children.value: Religion poisons the minds of individuals into submission, such is the anarchists' conviction. Dr. Mercier hints that many people will be immensely happy if you got rid of the archaic institution of the Church.

children.name: Text
children.value: There isn't a single church left on this island, I made sure of that. But the preachers... they still creep in our streets, spreading their poisonous creeds. We cannot allow this, it is our moral duty to put an end to this age of obscurantism!

children.name: Text
children.value: No matter how many churches Hugo brought to the ground, some pious preachers still remain on his island. As Hugo puts it, if you are a virtuous, you will help him find them and stop them from pouring their venom.

children.name: Text
children.value: Each individual must take part in the farming, learn the gruelling labour that goes into providing for their community. But... not everyone is yet equipped with harvesting skills, so the last batch was not... efficient. It's a growing process, I will not let them be discouraged by a small inconvenience! Send rations, no one needs to know.

children.name: Text
children.value: Hugo established a job rotation so everyone in his community will, at some point, learn what it's like to work on the fields. Unfortunately, many of them are not quite there yet, and they are having some trouble keeping up with the basic demands of the population. Hugo has asked you to deliver some food, all the better if no one ever gets to know it was you who filled up their storerooms...

children.name: Text
children.value: I would never dream of taking away people's right to revolt, but honestly, why can't these people understand that it takes some time to rebuild a new society? The issues they raise are nothing but a few bumps in our road to Utopia! You should talk some sense into them...

children.name: Text
children.value: People can sometimes be truly short-sighted. Those who expect immediate results will naturally become agitated at the first sign of any inconvenience. Gently persuade the rioters on Dr. Mercier's island that some times of trouble are to be expected on their way to a new society and they should keep quiet...

children.name: Text
children.value: People can be so slow witted! I have commissioned my favourite playwright to enact a play about the heroes of the Commune, and hopefully stimulate their minds and open their eyes to the unlimited benefits of our system. A sugar coating can make a pill easier to swallow, take a picture of the theatre goers to inform of the mandatory attendance. I will make sure they all look excited.

children.name: Text
children.value: Hugo is fed up with having to explain the benefits of anarchy to his comrades, so he will stage a play at which attendance is mandatory, a play he hopes will spark their intellects. Take a picture of the first batch of obligated theatre-goers to announce the event as if it were an exciting occasion.

children.name: Text
children.value: Brand new script from the revolutionary playwright Umberto Brocht will be premiered in Hugo Mercier's theatres. "It is my brainiest, driest, most didactical script thus far", declared the author about the mandatory cultural event. Preview attendants looked like they tried their very best to enjoy every bit of entertainment!

children.name: Text
children.value: The Establishment propaganda machine will have you believe that Anarchy is violent, chaotic, but it is them who abuse violence to amass power and tear down those who defy them. I need to let my people know that they shall not fear, for we have built a strong wall of defences to repel the weapons of the Capital.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Mercier wants to spread the message that his people need not worry about being attacked by capitalist powers, which is why he would like you to take and print a photograph of his solid harbour defences.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Hugo Mercier has worked on reinforcing his shore's incisors with plenty of metal fillings that will stop cloying capitalists from striking the nerves of his city.

children.name: Text
children.value: War reminds men of the things that truly matter. Hard even for these simpletons to complain about petty details with an enemy at our doorstep. They leave me no choice but to fabricate one...

children.name: Text
children.value: Hugo Mercier is having trouble keeping his people in line. He hopes focusing their energy on a war against a common enemy will distract them of the petty details that are raising their scepticism, but he needs your help for his charade.

children.name: Text
children.value: Landslide victory of Dr. Hugo Mercier casts away the fiendish enemies that wish to incarcerate his people within vicious liberalism. Trust towards their selfless leader reaches historical heights, as their profound sense of community strengthens in the face of adversity.

children.name: Text
children.value: As a leader, I am no ruler, I am a vessel. A vessel for the voice of every individual in this community. I need to hear their true voices, what their minds and hearts are claiming for. They would discuss it more openly to a neutral party, a party like you.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Hugo Mercier needs to hear the voice of his people in order to be a good leader for them, but he believes they will speak their minds more candidly to you.

children.name: Text
children.value: A survey conducted on Dr. Hugo Mercier's island reveals that a 100% of its population agrees with every direction their beloved leader steers them into.

children.name: Text
children.value: ... and we're almost out of medicam-... Oh! Hello, comrade! Our thoughts on Dr. Hugo? Well, things couldn't be going better! Yes, everything's fine, everything's absolutely perfect. Now, if you'll excuse me...

children.name: Text
children.value: ... what are we going to do when the cold comes b-...? Shh! Good day, comrade! Dr. Hugo? Yes, yes, he's the greatest leader we could ask for, we have nothing â€”absolutely nothingâ€” bad to say about him. Adieu.

children.name: Text
children.value: ... there's only so much left after my children are finished eat-... Wow, you startled me! What was I saying? Oh, never mind it... We looove Dr. Hugo, we do! And my children do too, yes, yes, very much so. Well, good day.

children.name: Text
children.value: Do not underestimate the dirty tricks the establishment is willing to use to undermine regimes such as ours. They have infiltrated our community and are now conspiring to take me down. Find them, they pretend to enjoy culture...

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Mercier is certain there is a group of infiltrators of the establishment conspiring to overthrow him. He has tasked you with finding them, they might be around one of the few places on Mercier's island that has something to do with entertainment.

children.name: Text
children.value: We are not conspirators, I swear! My children were hungry, I had to take a bit more than usual...! Please, please, do not take us to Dr. Hugo, we can take the next ferry out of here and you can just pretend you never saw us.

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh! Hello, yes. Apparently some people from our community have arrived at your docks... By mistake, yes, they were meaning to go... somewhere else. You see, they have no way of coming back, you must return them here â€”to their families and friends, of course.

children.name: Text
children.value: A group of people from Mercier's island have appeared at your docks. Never mind them saying that they mean to stay with you, they are a bit disoriented from the swaying of the ship and need your help to get back to their homes.

children.name: Text
children.value: Decayed traitors, willing to lick the boots of those whose stomp on us in exchange for shiny, meaningless trinkets! Wreck them, make an example out of them!

children.name: Text
children.value: A gang of traitors have fled Mercier's island, he has asked you to sink their ship and help him make an example out of them.

children.name: Text
children.value: Please, we have children with us, all we wanted was to live in peace. Have pity, please,  I will work for you!

children.name: Text
children.value: No sane person can see that many flaws in our perfect utopia. One of my mentors at the Academy of Medicine, Dr. Cotton, discovered mental illness to be but a reflection of untreated infections in the body. My people deserve to be cured. I will require her expertise, and some new tools...

children.name: Text
children.value: What is a greater indication of mental illness than the inability to recognise the many advantages of anarchy? Dr. Mercier needs some new tools and the knowledge of his former mentor, Dr. Harriet Cotton, to treat those who dissent against his policies.

children.name: Text
children.value: So long, Dr. Cotton. Please, make yourself at home. Yes, this is our first patient, he has already been numbed. So, which molar should I pull out...?

children.name: Text
children.value: If those separatists have time to dwell on harmful thoughts is because they are not working enough! Disorders of the mind vanish with every blister your burst for the well-being of your community. Gather my patients, I will ease their minds!

children.name: Text
children.value: More and more people are finding reasons to complain about Dr. Mercier's leadership. He of course considers this to be a fault of their foggy brains and has devised a way to clear them: excruciatingly tough labour.

children.name: Text
children.value: Remember, remember... how their so-called justice has failed and abused us all. A true envoy of Justice would blow up the very foundations of that crooked system. And from the smouldering remains, genuine freedom would arise....

children.name: Text
children.value: In an even more eloquent manner than usual, Dr. Hugo Mercier has suggested you to install a large volume of gunpowder around the landmark of Her Majesty's justice system: Wormways Prison.

children.name: Text
children.value: Gunpowder, treason and plot... such are the charges "Her Majesty" holds against me. Yet I am but a vessel that carries the indignant fire of a nation, on my way to ignite the blast that will demolish their fabricated order.

children.name: Text
children.value: In an almost overly dramatic move, Dr. Hugo has set a whole ship on fire as a metaphor for his bombastic leadership, that you are now to chaperon on its way to blow Wormways to pieces.

children.name: Text
children.value: I see no reason why this gunpowder treason should ever be forgot! May this historical moment leave a print for generations to follow!

children.name: Text
children.value: After the theatrical detonation on Wormways Prison, plenty of prisoners managed to escape from their cells and jump into the water. You can't just leave them to drown!

children.name: Text
children.value: Leon and I have stood together ever since we first picketed at the Academy, so... could it be? He contradicts my every decision, second guesses every word I say... It wouldn't be past that wretched Queen to hold my trust in my comrades against me...

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Hugo Mercier feels it, the prying gaze of his old comrade Leon on his every move, waiting for the perfect moment to sell him to the Queen... In order to either confirm or dissipate Mercier's doubts, you must follow the man and see what business he is truly up to.

children.name: Text
children.value: A fair trade again, Mr. Leon. I am surprised at your colleague Dr. Mercier, I reckoned an advocate for chaos would be a less reliable supplier. Do bring my compliments to him.

children.name: Text
children.value: A simple trade? He must have noticed you and concealed every sign of his betrayal... There must be something in his books that proves he is double-crossing our people, we must dig deeper!

children.name: Text
children.value: Far from being convinced of Leon's innocence, Dr. Mercier has urged you to go through his old colleague's personal records, both at his workplace and his home, and see if you can find any evidence to prove him guilty of treason.

children.name: Text
children.value: My apologies... We have looked everywhere and there is nothing at all that would lead anyone to believe that Leon is anything but a devoted anarchist and a competent representative of the people...

children.name: Text
children.value: What exactly are you looking for, is my Leon in trouble...? He's the most loyal man in the world, he talks with such passion about how exciting it is to be a part of this revolution hand in hand with his old friend Hugo...!

children.name: Text
children.value: Lies! Of course he made sure to erase every trace of his treachery! Or are you too on his side!? Prove it then! Sneak this into his ship's hold! I will expose the viper at any cost and save my people from his poison!

children.name: Text
children.value: Not yet satisfied with the results of your investigation, Dr. Mercier wants you to make sure that there is evidence to incriminate his old friend Leon of conspiring against their regime. Even if you have to create it yourselves.

children.name: Text
children.value: People from every corner of the world have joined our community ever since we embarked on this endeavour, but we haven't received any newcomers for months now... I have reasons to believe the Crown is blockading us. Someone must look into this...

children.name: Text
children.value: The number of people joining Dr. Mercier's Utopia has suddenly halted, and he suspects the Queen may be to blame. He needs you to conduct some investigations on the matter.

children.name: Text
children.value: Help! Please! We were attacked on our way to Dr. Hugo's utopia...! Oh, we worked so hard to build those ships and now... all of them, burnt to ashes...! Yes, they bore the Crown's sigil! Don't leave us here, I beg you...!

children.name: Text
children.value: Flamethrowers, so that's what that Queen has been up to...! Well, I guess the apple doesn't fall far from the tree after all. We will have to be very wary of them...

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh, hello! Yes, I merely intended to alert you about Dr. Mercier. He most definitely has a gift with words, but there may be less... consequential content in them than one might imagine. I believe your heart is in the right place... Please, bear this in mind in the future.

children.name: Text
children.value: We abhor violence, but the abuse of the Crown must be repaid! So many honest lives lost at sea, and their only crime was to believe a better world was possible! Enough! What goes around comes around.

children.name: Text
children.value: Unable to bear the Queen's pressure any longer, Dr. Mercier has asked you to help him warn her that any harm she does to his people will be returned.

children.name: Text
children.value: Whyever would you do that!? Attacks...? Well, I can assure you Her Majesty knows absolutely nothing about that! He is manipulating you like he manipulated all those people! Do not fall for it, I sincerely beg of you, stay loyal to your Queen...!

children.name: Text
children.value: You have earned our trust. My trust. Discreet as you always are, you will have no problems delivering this man to the royal residence unseen. Believe in me, it is of the utmost importance.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Mercier requires you to sneak past Sir Archibald patrols and make sure a very enigmatic masked man arrives unseen at High Clarence Hall docks. Where have you seen that mask before...?

children.name: Text
children.value: The fuse is burned down, we must brace for the grand finale. As a royal fleet heads for us, you must decide: are you willing to fight for enlightenment and equality, or will you support centuries of oppression and obscurantism?

children.name: Text
children.value: After months of tensions between Mercier and the Crown, the conflict is about to reach an armed resolution. You must now choose which side you are on: anarchy or monarchy.

children.name: Text
children.value: A true individual thinker! I am so proud of you, comrade! Here, our scientists have developed these explosives. Regrettably, we will very soon be needing them.

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh, dear, thank you for staying a sane constant throughout this most regrettable affair... Her Majesty didn't want things to come to this, but alas, it seems to be the only way now...

children.name: Text
children.value: The flame has risen, our job is done. Time to report back.

children.name: Text
children.value: You have spotted a mysterious ship that observed the battle from afar. Follow them and find out what their role was in the events that just unfolded.

children.name: Text
children.value: Everything went exactly as planned. Now both Mercier and the Queen are weak enough for us to take control. Igne Natura Renovatur! Wait, who are you...? Intruders! They mustn't escape!

children.name: Text
children.value: It can't be... were the Pyrphorians manipulating us all from the start? Oh, dear, Dr. Mercier really did believe it was us who attacked his people... I must speak to him at once, as much as we disagree, neither of us meant these hostilities.

children.name: Text
children.value: The... the Pyrphorians...? But... No, it was the Queen...! She hates our Utopia, she is a despot and a schemer! Those people must have been under her command all along! Yes.... yes, that's it...

children.name: Text
children.value: Sir Archibald Blake has requested your presence at High Clarence Hall to discuss a touchy subject.

children.name: Text
children.value: Sir Archibald Blake has requested your presence at High Clarence Hall immediately.

children.name: Text
children.value: Who are you to refuse your people the knowledge of anarchy? Publish anarchist propaganda on your newspaper, or Dr. Mercier will assume you are against it.

children.name: Text
children.value: Open up your Newspaper's draft and click edit. Then drag one of the stipulated articles and replace the standard news.

children.value:
Publish on your Newspaper:
At least 1 Anarchist Propaganda Article

children.name: Text
children.value:

children.name: Text
children.value:

Help them escape:

children.name: Text
children.value:
OR:
Sail to Mercier's Revolutionary Clipper to side with him

children.name: Text
children.value:
EITHER:
Sail to Archibald Blake's Lighthouse to defend the crown

children.name: Text
children.value: Find the torchbearer running around the streets of your city.

children.name: Text
children.value: The priests are being persecuted by workers down the streets of your city.

children.name: Text
children.value: The anarchists are gathered around a fire, hiding in your city.

children.name: Text
children.value: Anarchists are burning books around your city.

children.name: Text
children.value: Find the rioting mobs stomping down the streets of Dr. Hugo Mercier's city.

children.name: Text
children.value: Look for the conspirators near Dr. Mercier's variety theatre.

children.name: Text
children.value: Look for the preachers near Dr. Mercier's marketplace, trade union and town hall.

children.name: Text
children.value: Find the dissidents hiding near Dr. Mercier's worker residences.

children.name: Text
children.value: Talk to Dr. Mercier's residents at the variety theatre, the town hall and the trade union.

children.name: Text
children.value: In order to turn your passive trade balance positive, make sure to sell more goods at your trading post than you are buying.

children.name: Text
children.value: Some anarchy defectors have escaped from Dr. Mercier and are requesting asylum on your island.

children.name: Text
children.value: Anarchy defectors thank you for your kindness.

children.name: Text
children.value: Anarchy defectors would like to thank you with a gift.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Hugo Mercier smirks at the trouble his infiltrators are creating on your island.

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Mercier promised us an utopia, but the things we saw there... We have managed to escape his totalitarian hell, but now we have nowhere to go. All we want is an honest life; please, let us live here!

children.name: Text
children.value: When you see the happy smiling faces among Dr. Mercier's commune, you know their struggles are over, their pain is over. Why not show your own people what they're missing?

children.name: Text
children.value: Your people are envious of life in Dr. Mercier's commune. They are insisting you publish an image of one of his islands in your newspaper â€” even if it tarnishes your own reputation in the process.

children.name: Text
children.value: An unprecedented photographic report illustrates the idyllic life of people in Dr. Hugo Mercier's island, where all individuals are equal and not one is better clothed or fed than their neighbour.

children.name: Text
children.value: The folk who came over from Dr. Mercier have opened our eyes! If we have skill to fashion products from steel, then it is us entitled to that product, not you!

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Mercier's ideas are spreading among your residents, and they begin to realise it is only you who benefits from all they produce. They demand a large quantity of the steel beams and weapons they sweated over be awarded to them.

children.name: Text
children.value: Oi, boss, ever heard of the labour theory of value? It is our sweat and blisters that should give gubbins their pricetag! Yet our wages are risible compared to what those soft-handed artisans get. Redress the balance before we break it!

children.name: Text
children.value: The workers have gotten acquainted with some bits of anarchist theory and now they demand to be compensated for all the lost value of their labour in the capitalist free market.

children.name: Text
children.value: Bread is but the basics of a meal! Are you a stuck up bourgeois that will just tell the common people to "eat brioche"? Hand out the loaves, now!

children.name: Text
children.value: Your workers will not settle for the crumbs! If you want to keep your empire from crumbling from within, you better keep their bellies full.

children.name: Text
children.value: We workers know what we are doing, let us manage our own! Give us a space to unite and decide collectively, as they do over at Dr. Hugo's!

children.name: Text
children.value: Your workers are claiming their rights to control and manage the means of production. A trade union would be the perfect space for them to come together and debate.

children.name: Text
children.value: You intoxicate us with the lies of priests to keep us compliant in the face of oppression! We don't want any more churches, give us temples of democracy instead!

children.name: Text
children.value: Your workers are fed up with having their minds numbed by religion. They will have you take down a church and replace it with a town hall, or else...

children.name: Text
children.value: As long as we depend on the trade from other nations we are hostages to the free market! You better make sure we are not buying more than we are selling!

children.name: Text
children.value: It is important for your workers that you make sure your nation is self-sufficient and doesn't rely on the trade from other nations. They will not be satisfied until your gross domestic product is in the positive.

children.name: Text
children.value: If we must play along the laws of capitalism, then let's! If supply becomes ridiculously high, prices will have to drop. Maybe to the point where anyone could just help themselves to whatever they need!

children.name: Text
children.value: Overproducing, Mercier argues, is actually a good thing for the people, since the prices drop so much it becomes unnecessary to track who helps themselves to what. That is what your workers want for your island too.

children.name: Text
children.value: Why build so many police stations, are you scared of the voice of the people? We will not tolerate this authoritarian repression, try and address our problems instead!

children.name: Text
children.value: When police is everywhere, justice is nowhere. So have your workers come to believe after learning more of anarchy. They have destroyed all your police stations and their violence will resume if you can't maintain the peace without them.

children.name: Text
children.value: Your laws protect the privileged! It's time you legislate for the people, or we'll snap the entire system!

children.name: Text
children.value: Fed up with an unjust system, your people demand you institute laws that protect the common classes.

children.name: Text
children.value: Our new anarchist peers have opened our eyes to the evils of society! The boys made this poster at the union to spread the word. I reckon you will see no issue in putting it up on our town hall, right?

children.name: Text
children.value: Your workers are thrilled by everything they are learning about anarchy. They are so engaged in it that they have stayed overnight preparing a poster to paste to your town hall walls.

children.name: Text
children.value: You embody the establishment! We will join Dr. Hugo's commune and become free, equal individuals! You want to prove you are a decent human being? Then don't be a sore loser and shelter our path!

children.name: Text
children.value: There is no stopping these workers from leaving your island to join Dr. Mercier's people, but if you still want to be decent towards them, you can make sure they have a safe travel there.

children.name: Text
children.value: No wonder we are turning against capitalism when we lead such pathetic lives. If we were twice as happy we wouldn't be looking for a way out!

children.name: Text
children.value: The only reason why your workers are starting to find anarchy attractive is because they are miserable. Well, maybe not miserable, but they could certainly be happier!

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Hugo is the brightest mind of the century! If he doesn't respect you, why should we!?

children.name: Text
children.value: You are at odds with Dr. Hugo Mercier, which means your workers â€”who look up to the anarchist leaderâ€” are at odds with you. Perhaps winning the heart of the doctor will earn you the love of your people.

children.name: Text
children.value: As workers, labour is our greatest power! So say the lads that came over from Mercier's, they feel mighty good after a long day of hard work. Come on, let's add some more fuel!

children.name: Text
children.value: Dr. Hugo's anarchist theory says that the greatest power of a worker stems from their labour, when all the benefits stay within their community. You are not sure if your workers understand the full picture, but they do want to work harder, so who are you to argue against them.

children.name: Text
children.value: With so much talk about the evils of religion, priests are starting to be persecuted! Even if you agree, no soul deserves to be threatened because of their beliefs. Protect them!

children.name: Text
children.value: The anarchist mistrust of the clergy has spread to your population. It appears some of your workers are harassing priests! A concerned citizen has asked you to find and defend them.

children.name: Text
children.value: Oh, no. Oh, there you are! Yes, I just heard something very â€”deeply!â€” vexing.  It appears anarchists are planning an attack! Oh, you must stop the man with the torch, I beg of you!

children.name: Text
children.value: A panicked artisan came looking for your help. He overheard a group of anarchists speaking about an impending attack on your city. Find the man bearing the torch before it's too late!

children.name: Text
children.value: Inspector Langdon says they're too busy chasing away anarchist troublemakers to look into the vanishing of my hens! Can't you give them a hand...?

children.name: Text
children.value: The police has been overwhelmed trying to uncover the anarchist infiltrators lately, but your people have other problems they need their help with! Help them unearth the anarchist gangs to free some space on their plate.

children.name: Text
